04472nam a22006855i 9781501717987DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017179877 a10.7591/97815017179872doi  a(DE-B1597)503264  a(OCoLC)1038495478  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDC33.4.S553 2005 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a305.5/22/0944090331 aSmith, Jay M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNobility Reimagined :bThe Patriotic Nation in Eighteenth-Century France /cJay M. Smith. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b13 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIlustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbrevations -- tIntroduction: Honor, Virtue, And Patriotism In Eighteenth-Century France -- t1. Nobility And The Appeal To Virtue In Early Eighteenth-Century France (17005-17405) -- t2. Nobility And The Longing For Virtue: Patriotic Possibilities From Montesquieu To Mirabeau -- t3. Patriotism And Social Taxonomy In The Debate Over La Noblesse Commerfante -- t4. Patriotic Resurgence And The Nationalization Of Honor (17608-1780) -- t5. Nobility In A Nation Of Citizens (I76os-Early 17805) -- t6. Defining Nobility And Nation In 1788-1789 -- tConclusion: Patriotic Revolution -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe mature nationalism that fueled the French Revolution grew from patriotic sensibilities fostered over the course of a century or more. Jay M. Smith proposes that the French thought their way to nationhood through a process of psychic adjustment premised on the reimagining of nobility, a social category and moral concept that had long dominated the cultural horizons of the old regime. Nobility Reimagined follows the elaboration of French patriotism across the eighteenth century and highlights the accentuation of key, and conflicting, features of patriotic thought at defining moments in the history of the monarchy. By enabling the articulation of different futures for nobility and nation, the patriotic awakening that marked the old regime helped to create both the quest for patriotic unity and the fierce constitutional battles that flowered at the time of the Revolution. Smith argues that the attempt to redefine and restore French nobility brought forth competing visions of patriotism with correlating models of the social and political order. Although the terms of public debate have changed, the same basic challenge continues to animate contemporary politics: how to reconcile inspiring and unifying nationalist ideals—honor, virtue, patriotism—with persistent social frictions rooted in class, ideology, ethnicity, or gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNobilityzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPatriotismzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171798740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717987423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717987/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK